#Text=active cave - a cave which has a stream flowing in it.

#Text=aeolian calcarenite - a limestone formed on land by solution and redeposition of calcium carbonate in coastal dune sands containing a large proportion of calcareous sand from mollusc shells and other organic remains.
#Text=aragonite - a less common crystalline form of calcium carbonate than calcite, denser and orthorhombic.
#Text=bare karst - karst with much exposed bedrock.
#Text=bathyphreatic - referring to water moving with some speed through downward looping passages in the phreatic zone.
#Text=bed - a depositional layer of sedimentary bedrock or. unconsolidated sediment.
#Text=bedding-grike - a narrow, rectilinear slot in a karst rock outcrop as a result of solution along a bedding-plane.
#Text=bedding plane - a surface separating two beds, usually planar.
#Text=bedding-plane cave - a cavity developed along a bedding-plane and elongate in cross-section as a result.
#Text=biospeleology - the scientific study of organisms living in caves.
#Text=blind shaft - a vertical extension upwards from part of a cave but not reaching the surface; small in area in relation to its height.
#Text=blind valley - a valley that is closed abruptly at its lower end by a cliff or slope facing up the valley.
#Text=blowhole - a hole to the surface in the roof of a sea cave through which waves force air and water.
#Text=blowhole - a hole in the ground through which air blows in and out strongly, sometimes audibly; common in the nullarbor plain.
#Text=branchwork - a dendritic system of underground streams or passages wherein branches join successively to form a major stream or passage.
